<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>This year, 636 814 full-time and 161 475 part-time have registered to sit for the matric exams.KZN and Gauteng have the largest number of pupils enrolled, with 169 023 and 112 164 respectively. Limpopo has 110 639 while the Eastern Cape registered 92 755 candidates. The department said preparations had also been made for matrics in Vuwani, Limpopo to write in the wake of yet another shutdown. The department said the registration of National Senior Certificate exam centres and candidates had been completed. “Question papers have been set and externally moderated,” said department spokesman Elijah Mhlanga. “To prevent leaks in 2017 question papers, all 212 storage points across the country have been audited to ensure minimum security standards. “Storage points that don’t comply will not be allowed to store question papers.”